properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Winds of 70 km/h near exposed coastal areas will develop near noon Tuesday and ease late Tuesday evening. An intense front will approach Vancouver Island early Tuesday and cross the Lower Mainland Tuesday night. The front will bring rain and strong winds for most of Tuesday, with the strongest winds expected Tuesday afternoon and evening. Winds will ease Tuesday night as the front passes. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy rain will begin this morning over West Vancouver Island. Total rainfall amounts in excess of 100 mm are expected by this evening. Yet another frontal system will move across Vancouver Island on Tuesday. This system will bring heavy rain and strong winds to West Vancouver Island beginning in the morning. The heaviest rainfall rates are expected through the afternoon and early evening. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Very strong wind gusts that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A strong pacific front will approach Haida Gwaii overnight and cross the archipelago Tuesday morning. Very strong winds will accompany the front and spread to all coastal regions of the BC North Coast on Tuesday. Winds will increase to southeast 90 to 120 km/h over Haida Gwaii early Tuesday morning and ease to south 40 to 60 km/h near noon. Winds will rise to southeast 90 km/h gusting to 110 over the exposed areas of North Vancouver Island, Central Coast- Coastal and North Coast - Coastal regions on Tuesday morning and ease to south 50 km/h late in the afternoon. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of mixed winter weather expected for the latter half of this week. Locations: Eastern and southeastern Labrador, as well as the Upper Lake Melville area. Time span: Beginning Wednesday morning and lasting into the weekend. The end time is uncertain at this point. Details for Wednesday: Snow, ice pellets, freezing rain, and rain will affect southeastern Labrador and the Upper Lake Melville area. Snowfall amounts will range from 10 to 20 cm inland by Thursday morning, with rainfall amounts of 10 to 20 mm along the coast. A significant area of freezing rain is likely to occur inland as well. Details for Thursday to Sunday: All above mentioned forms of precipitation will continue through Thursday and likely Friday as well, with significant amounts of each. At this time, it looks as if conditions will begin to improve in some areas on Saturday, but may continue in other areas into Sunday. Further details will be provided in subsequent messages, as it is too soon to accurately forecast amounts and duration of precipitation due to uncertainty. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2021-01-05T18:43:26-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of mixed winter weather expected for the latter half of this week. Locations: Southeastern Labrador. Total rainfall through Wednesday night: 10 to 15 mm along the coast south of Black Tickle. Total snow and ice pellets through Wednesday night: 10 to 20 cm in the Cartwright area. Time span: beginning overnight tonight and lasting into the weekend. The end time is uncertain at this point. Remarks: Snow and ice pellets will develop over southeastern Labrador late overnight tonight and will quickly change to rain Wednesday morning along the coast south of Black Tickle. Motorists travelling the Trans labrador Highway from Red Bay to Cartwright Junction will likely experience periods of freezing rain Wednesday and Wednesday night, especially over higher terrain. For the Cartwright area, precipitation will fall primarily as a mix of snow and ice pellets Wednesday and Wednesday night. with a risk of freezing rain. All above mentioned forms of precipitation will continue through Thursday and likely Friday as well, with potentially significant amounts of each. At this time, it looks as if conditions will begin to improve on Saturday. Further details will be provided in subsequent forecasts, as it is too soon to accurately forecast amounts and duration of precipitation due to uncertainty. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of snow expected for the latter half of this week. Locations: the mid Labrador coast from Rigolet to Makkovik, as well as the Upper Lake Melville area. Time span: beginning late in the day on Wednesday and lasting into the weekend. The end time is uncertain at this point. Remarks: Snow will develop in the Rigolet area Wednesday afternoon before spreading to Postville-Makkovik and the Upper Lake Melville area Wednesday night. Snow is expected to persist through Thursday and likely Friday as well, with significant accumulations possible. At this time, it looks as if conditions will begin to improve in some areas on Saturday, but may continue in other areas into Sunday. Further details will be provided in subsequent messages, as it is too soon to accurately forecast amounts and duration of precipitation due to uncertainty. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
